        "range": "3:24-26",
        "excerpt": "being justified as a gift by His grace through the redemption which is in Christ Jesus; whom God displayed publicly as a propitiation in His blood through faith.",
        "body": "These three verses are the densest doctrine in the New Testament. Luther: *the chief point, and the very central place of the Epistle, and of the whole Bible.* Cranfield called them *the centre and heart of the whole of Romans 1:16-15:13.* Every word counts.\n\n*Being justified as a gift by His grace through the redemption which is in Christ Jesus* (3:24). Four foundational words pile together. **Justified** (*dikaioumenoi*) — declared righteous in God's court. **As a gift** (*dōrean*) — gratuitously, without cause in the recipient (the same word Jesus uses in John 15:25, *they hated Me without cause*). **By His grace** (*tē autou chariti*) — by His unearned favor as the active source. **Through the redemption** (*dia tēs apolytrōseōs*) — through the ransom-paid release, the slave-market and exodus background that runs through Paul. Every word excludes human contribution. The justification is gratuitous (gift), gracious (grace), and costly (redemption — to Him).\n\n*Whom God displayed publicly as a propitiation in His blood through faith* (3:25). The verb *proetheto* — *displayed publicly, set forth, exhibited* — emphasizes that the cross was not a private transaction but a public exhibit. Golgotha was outside Jerusalem in broad daylight, witnessed by Jew and Gentile, Roman soldier and weeping woman. Then comes the chapter's most contested noun: *hilastērion*. In the LXX of Exodus 25:17-22 and seventeen occurrences in Leviticus 16, *hilastērion* is the gold lid of the ark of the covenant — the *mercy seat*, the place where the high priest sprinkled sacrificial blood on Yom Kippur, and the place where God's wrath against the covenant people's sin was turned aside. Paul says Christ is now *that place*. The translation choice between *propitiation* (wrath-absorbing) and *expiation* (sin-removing) has divided exegetes — C. H. Dodd argued for *expiation* on the grounds that pagan gods are propitiated but the God of Israel is not. Leon Morris (in *The Apostolic Preaching of the Cross*) decisively answered Dodd: the Old Testament repeatedly speaks of God's wrath that must be turned aside, and the New Testament inherits that vocabulary. The cross is *both* expiation (sin removed) *and* propitiation (wrath absorbed) — and the wrath belongs to God Himself, against whom we have sinned and who Himself provides the satisfaction. Christ is both the offended party and the means of reconciliation.\n\nThe purpose follows: *this was to demonstrate His righteousness, because in the forbearance of God He passed over the sins previously committed* (3:25b). This is one of Paul's most theologically penetrating moves. The cross looks **backward** as well as forward. In Old Testament times, God *passed over* (*paresin*, a different word from *aphesis* / forgiveness — more like temporary deferment, a moratorium) sins of His covenant people in His forbearance. But this raised a question: how could a righteous God forgive David's adultery, Abraham's deceit, Manasseh's idolatry? Was God lax? Paul's answer: God's forbearance with past sins was not laxity but anticipation. The cross retroactively vindicates every Old Testament forgiveness, because the satisfaction is now made. The blood of bulls and goats never took away sins (Hebrews 10:4); but it pointed forward to the blood that did, and on the basis of that future event God could justly defer punishment for past sins.\n\nVerse 26 reaches the chapter's apex: *for the demonstration, I say, of His righteousness at the present time, so that He would be just and the justifier of the one who has faith in Jesus*. The problem the cross solves is not merely the sinner's guilt; it is the apparent tension between God's holiness and God's mercy. If God simply forgives without satisfaction, He is not *just* — He has indulged sin. If God simply punishes without provision, He is not *justifier* — sinners remain condemned. The cross resolves the tension by punishing sin in Christ as substitute, so that the sinner who trusts Christ is truly acquitted on grounds that uphold rather than compromise divine justice. J. I. Packer (in *Knowing God*, chapter 18) called this the highest expression of God's wisdom in Scripture: God devises a way to be merciful without ceasing to be just, and just without ceasing to be merciful.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Hilastērion* (3:25) — in the LXX of Exodus 25:17-22 the *kapporet*, the mercy seat. The cognate verb *hilaskomai* appears in Hebrews 2:17 of Christ. *Proetheto* (3:25) — to set forth publicly, exhibit, propose; here of God's public display of Christ on the cross. *Paresin* (3:25) — *passing over* in the sense of temporary deferral, used only here in the NT; deliberately distinct from *aphesis* (forgiveness, release). *Endeixis* (3:25, 26) — proof, demonstration, public legal exhibit. *Dikaion kai dikaiounta* (3:26) — *just and justifying*, the two cognates side by side; the chiastic structure underscores the simultaneity."
